spec: ab3256
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__ dict-presence (reflected power/shift) for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__rpow__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __rpow__. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic semantics — n ** ABC is not a defined Python operation and ABC has no __rpow__ to provide a fallback. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities involve reflected power. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __rpow__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not numeric types. n ** f is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__rlshift__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __rlshift__. Reflected left shift (__rlshift__) is the complement of __lshift__. abc.ABC defines no bitwise or shift operators — neither __lshift__ nor __rlshift__ appear in its __dict__. abc.ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery; left shift is entirely absent. The function type does not define __rlshift__; n << f is not a valid Python expression for callable objects. Note: Python's logging.Logger defines __lshift__ as a convenience for chaining handlers, but function objects and abc types do not."
    - "Key finding (__rrshift__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __rrshift__. Reflected right shift (__rrshift__) is invoked when n >> obj is attempted and the left operand does not handle the right operand. abc.ABC has no numeric, bitwise, or shift data model. abc.ABCMeta handles abstract method tracking and class hierarchy; none of its responsibilities map to reflected right shift. The function type does not define __rrshift__; n >> f is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 663 (__rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, and reflected dunder tested across 13 consecutive waves (652–664). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __rpow__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__rpow__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __rpow__.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no
#   arithmetic or reflected-arithmetic semantics. n ** ABC is not a defined
#   Python operation; ABC has no __rpow__ to serve as a fallback.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. Reflected power has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities
#   (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__).
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __rpow__. n ** f is not a valid Python
#   expression for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors
#   with no numeric data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3256.rpow:
  description: "abc types __rpow__ dict-presence checks; wave 664"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3256

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3256001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__rpow__"], false]
    - ["ab3256002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__rpow__"], false]
    - ["ab3256003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__rpow__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __rlshift__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__rlshift__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __rlshift__.
# abc.ABC: no bitwise or shift data model; neither __lshift__ nor
#   __rlshift__ appear in abc.ABC's __dict__. ABC is a pure abstract base
#   class helper with no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __rlshift__ for metaclass reflected left
#   shift. ABCMeta's API surface (__subclasshook__, register(),
#   __abstractmethods__) has no bitwise or shift component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __rlshift__. n << f is not a valid Python
#   expression for callable objects. Note: logging.Logger overloads <<
#   as a handler-chaining convenience, but function objects do not belong
#   to that convention. The function type is tightly scoped to its role
#   as a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3256.rlshift:
  description: "abc types __rlshift__ dict-presence checks; wave 664"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3256

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3256004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__rlshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3256005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__rlshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3256006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__rlshift__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __rrshift__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__rrshift__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __rrshift__.
# abc.ABC: no numeric, bitwise, or shift data model; n >> ABC is not a
#   defined Python expression. abc.ABC is a bare metaclass convenience
#   wrapper with no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __rrshift__ for reflected right shift.
#   ABCMeta is a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in
#   class-hierarchy machinery — not in operator overloading.
#   n >> ABCMeta is not a valid Python expression.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __rrshift__. Unlike some pipeline frameworks
#   that overload >> as a chaining operator, CPython's built-in function
#   type has no __rrshift__. n >> f is not a valid Python expression for
#   callable objects.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3256.rrshift:
  description: "abc types __rrshift__ dict-presence checks; wave 664"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3256

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3256007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__rrshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3256008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__rrshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3256009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__rrshift__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __rpow__: false for all 3.
# __rlshift__: false for all 3.
# __rrshift__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 663 (__rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__, __and__, __or__, __xor__,
#          __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__,
#          __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
#   a display representation. All arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, and
#   reflected power/shift operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic,
#   bitwise, and reflected dunder tested across 13 consecutive waves (652–664).
#   Its power lies exclusively in class-hierarchy machinery — not in operator
#   overloading of any kind.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, or power/shift protocol
#   whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

